The Chronicle Updates by Nduduzo Tshuma and Prosper Ndlovu 13:30 – President Mnangagwa and his delegation have proceeded to another mine, Jinan/Tutu Mine coke project. He is now in a closed door briefing. 13:25 – President Mnangagwa ends his speech. 13:20 – “A programme is unfolding in the sector, a shame for us to be improving food when we have agricultural land. Only 10 percent of water bodies being used but we have a programme to develop smart agriculture. Let’s take on board ICTs to industrialise and modernise our industry and commerce.” <img class="alignnone wp-image-504331 size-large" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.50.53-680x418.jpeg" alt="" width="680" height="418" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.50.53.jpeg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.50.53-360x221.jpeg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> 13:15 – “We need harmony and peace in our community to achieve these, no one can come and tell us to unite and use our resources. Our highly educated population must contribute to national development and be patriotic. <img class="alignnone wp-image-504329 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.50.52.jpeg" alt="" width="679" height="408" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.50.52.jpeg 679w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.50.52-360x216.jpeg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 679px) 100vw, 679px" /> “We have food insecurity in the country, but we must plan to use technology of irrigation so that whether drought on not we still can feed ourselves. 13:10 – “Hwange is somewhat behind in terms of infrastructure development, we need no area to be behind. Companies here should address challenges of water, social amenities like schools and clinics, and road infrastructure here. <img class="alignnone wp-image-504326 size-large" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.50.51-680x403.jpeg" alt="" width="680" height="403" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.50.51.jpeg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.50.51-360x213.jpeg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> “Government is there but needs private sector support. National challenges not for government alone, but all of us towards betterment of lives of our people. “We assure the companies investing here of government support to grow. Importation of energy and energy products must be a thing of the past because we have enough resources to produce it, even producing fuel, if we remain focused. Competencies and skills of doing that are there in the market and we should attract them. <img class="alignnone wp-image-504324 size-large" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.50.49-680x393.jpeg" alt="" width="680" height="393" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.50.49.jpeg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.50.49-360x208.jpeg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> 13:02 – “To achieve the vision there is need for a stable, united, harmonious country and supportive stakeholders with other sub-sectors of the economy contributing. After Chitando’s presentation I was satisfied that the mandate and task I gave him to me seems achievable as mining firms show commitment to expansion and growth. “We need those in Government and private sector and communities around to all pull in one direction, in unison. Our desire is to achieve higher middle income by 2030, this won’t be achieved by mining alone but all sectors. <img class="alignnone wp-image-504321 size-large" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.50.47-680x411.jpeg" alt="" width="680" height="411" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.50.47.jpeg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.50.47-360x218.jpeg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> “It does seem mining sector vision is on course, no doubt we will achieve the vision we have set. These firms we have engaged to value addition and processing give preference to locals in jobs… 13:00 – President now takes to the podium to address the gathering. President Mnangagwa says he is impressed by the articulation of the mining sector vision by mines minister Winston Chitando towards achieving $12bn earnings by 2023. 12:50 – Official proceedings rolling now, South Mining managing director Mr Chenji Li, now delivering his remarks. <img class="alignnone wp-image-504318 size-large" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.52.18-680x377.jpeg" alt="" width="680" height="377" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.52.18.jpeg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.52.18-360x200.jpeg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> He says their company has received a lot of support locally in establishing the  plant. He pays tribute to Hwange community and stakeholders and Government for creating a supportive investment climate. 12:48 – President Mnangagwa is now touring the new coke plant. He is accompanied by Industry Minister Dr Sekai Nzenza, Mines Minister Winston Chitando, Mangaliso Ndlovu (environment), Presidential spokesperson George Charamba. <img class="alignnone wp-image-504310 size-large" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.42.12-680x377.jpeg" alt="" width="680" height="377" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.42.12.jpeg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.42.12-360x200.jpeg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> <img class="alignnone wp-image-504307 size-large" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.42.14-680x377.jpeg" alt="" width="680" height="377" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.42.14.jpeg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.42.14-360x200.jpeg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> PREAMBLE President Mnangagwa arrived in Hwange in Matabeleland North tour coal mining and power generation projects, which are being implemented in fulfillment of his promise to ensure realisation of the province’s full economic potential. He is currently in a closed door meeting at South Mining plant with the mine officials before official commissioning of the new plant. <img class="alignnone wp-image-504303 size-large" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/ED-in-Hwange-680x385.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="385" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/ED-in-Hwange.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/ED-in-Hwange-360x204.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> In the morning President Mnangagwa presided over the ground breaking ceremony of Western Coal and Energy Company Private Limited. <img class="alignnone wp-image-504300 size-large" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.17.47-680x377.jpeg" alt="" width="680" height="377" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.17.47.jpeg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.17.47-360x200.jpeg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> The devolution thrust is set to transform the province previously viewed as lagging behind in terms of development despite its vast natural resources. <img class="alignnone wp-image-504297 size-large" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.17.48-680x377.jpeg" alt="" width="680" height="377" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.17.48.jpeg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2020/07/WhatsApp-Image-2020-07-16-at-12.17.48-360x200.jpeg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> The coal, coke and energy value chain alone has the potential to transform the province and create thousands of jobs. Riding under the new dispensation’s devolution drive, the coal sector, combined with other critical sectors such as tourism, timber, gold mining and agriculture, could rapidly propel the province to greater heights.